WEBVTT

00:01.909 --> 00:03.669
<i>- The most violent drug lord
in history.</i>

00:03.828 --> 00:07.006
<i>- Part of El Chapo's rise
is just how ruthless he was.</i>

00:07.165 --> 00:10.167
Innocent people would be caught
in the crossfire.

00:10.251 --> 00:13.670
<i>- The most secure prison
in Mexico.</i>

00:13.763 --> 00:16.181
<i>- Chapo's incarcerated
in Altiplano prison,</i>

00:16.266 --> 00:17.850
which is super-maximum security.

00:18.009 --> 00:20.677
- It was thought
to be impregnable.

00:20.770 --> 00:24.264
<i>- And a daring attempt
to break in.</i>

00:24.357 --> 00:26.516
<i>- A one-mile tunnel.</i>

00:26.601 --> 00:30.187
How would you be able
to pinpoint where to come up?

00:30.271 --> 00:31.697
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:31.856 --> 00:35.192
<i>- You can see him pacing back
and forth in the cell,</i>

00:35.276 --> 00:39.362
<i>and then all of a sudden,
he's gone.</i>

00:39.447 --> 00:44.451
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:44.544 --> 00:49.214
- Some of the greatest stories
ever told start behind bars.

00:49.373 --> 00:50.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:50.958 --> 00:52.876
<i>Locked up in the most
notorious prisons</i>

00:52.960 --> 00:54.553
<i>in the world,</i>

00:54.712 --> 00:58.223
<i>spied on by guards
and fellow prisoners.</i>

00:59.383 --> 01:02.728
<i>It takes a devious mind
to find a way out.</i>

01:04.639 --> 01:07.557
<i>It could lead you to freedom.</i>

01:07.650 --> 01:09.902
<i>Or it could cost you your life.</i>

01:11.312 --> 01:13.906
<i>But wouldn't you try,</i>

01:14.065 --> 01:15.565
when you have nothing left
to lose?

01:15.650 --> 01:19.369
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:22.490 --> 01:25.584
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:25.743 --> 01:32.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:32.333 --> 01:34.084
This is an isolation cell

01:34.177 --> 01:37.587
in Federal Social Readaptation
Center Number Two,

01:37.672 --> 01:39.848
known as Puente Grande,

01:40.007 --> 01:43.602
just outside
of Guadalajara, Mexico.

01:43.686 --> 01:45.437
To escape means overcoming layer

01:45.522 --> 01:48.941
after layer
of impenetrable walls

01:49.100 --> 01:52.444
and an army of guards
that outnumber the inmates

01:52.529 --> 01:55.021
almost two-to-one.

01:55.106 --> 01:57.607
Seem like overkill?

01:57.700 --> 02:00.193
Not if you're dealing
with a very special class

02:00.278 --> 02:03.363
of criminal--the drug lord.

02:03.456 --> 02:06.449
[helicopter whirring]

02:06.534 --> 02:09.628
<i>Drug lords have
their own private armies,</i>

02:09.712 --> 02:13.966
<i>so the walls of Puente Grande
need to be able to withstand</i>

02:14.125 --> 02:17.469
<i>a full-scale assault
from the outside.</i>

02:18.880 --> 02:21.715
<i>Above the walls,
armed guards and towers</i>

02:21.799 --> 02:23.550
<i>keep an eye on everything</i>

02:23.643 --> 02:27.146
<i>and everyone that comes
and goes from this lock-up.</i>

02:27.230 --> 02:32.568
<i>Any attempt to get in or out
must avoid their watchful eye.</i>

02:33.811 --> 02:37.480
- Puente Grande had
a vast surveillance

02:37.565 --> 02:39.983
and security apparatus.

02:40.067 --> 02:43.745
<i>It was the place that
narco-criminals were sent.</i>

02:43.905 --> 02:46.323
<i>It was thought
to be impregnable.</i>

02:46.416 --> 02:49.418
- This cell is home
to one of the most

02:49.502 --> 02:51.920
notorious and bloodthirsty
narco-criminals

02:52.005 --> 02:54.581
of all time...

02:54.665 --> 02:59.502
Joaquín Guzmán,
known to the world as El Chapo.

02:59.587 --> 03:05.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:06.010 --> 03:08.604
<i>He's a billionaire, a murderer,</i>

03:08.763 --> 03:10.689
<i>and a folk hero.</i>

03:10.773 --> 03:13.525
To the Mexican government,

03:13.610 --> 03:16.770
he's just
public enemy number one.

03:16.854 --> 03:19.773
- El Chapo is the 21st century's

03:19.857 --> 03:22.359
narco-celebrity
of all narco-celebrities.

03:22.443 --> 03:24.110
[chatter]

03:24.195 --> 03:26.112
- If you ask anybody, he's still

03:26.206 --> 03:27.956
the most feared drug trafficker
in the world.

03:28.115 --> 03:29.449
<i>There are places in Mexico</i>

03:29.533 --> 03:32.461
<i>where his name
is just whispered now.</i>

03:32.620 --> 03:36.632
<i>Part of El Chapo's rise
is just how ruthless he was.</i>

03:36.716 --> 03:38.375
<i>There were certainly
tens of thousands,</i>

03:38.459 --> 03:41.044
<i>if not more
that were collateral damage</i>

03:41.137 --> 03:43.472
as a result
of the raging drug war

03:43.556 --> 03:45.390
that he was at the center of.

03:45.549 --> 03:47.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:47.635 --> 03:51.972
<i>- Joaquín Guzmán starts
growing marijuana in 1972,</i>

03:52.056 --> 03:53.723
<i>and rises quickly</i>

03:53.808 --> 03:56.401
<i>in the violent
international drug trade.</i>

03:56.560 --> 03:59.488
<i>By 1989, he's head
of the infamous</i>

03:59.647 --> 04:02.399
<i>Sinaloa Cartel.</i>

04:02.492 --> 04:04.150
<i>But during a bloody turf battle</i>

04:04.244 --> 04:06.152
<i>with a rival cartel,</i>

04:06.246 --> 04:09.906
<i>a beloved Catholic bishop
is killed in the crossfire,</i>

04:09.999 --> 04:13.910
<i>and El Chapo becomes
a wanted man.</i>

04:13.995 --> 04:15.921
- As a result of this,
the Mexican government

04:16.005 --> 04:17.914
mounted a massive manhunt.

04:17.999 --> 04:19.091
[gunfire]

04:19.250 --> 04:21.584
<i>They finally apprehended him
in Guatemala</i>

04:21.669 --> 04:24.096
<i>in June 1993.</i>

04:24.180 --> 04:27.766
And from there, he goes
to Puente Grande prison.

04:27.925 --> 04:30.343
<i>- But despite the prison's
intense security,</i>

04:30.428 --> 04:32.762
<i>Puente Grande doesn't
turn out to be</i>

04:32.847 --> 04:34.606
<i>such a bad place for El Chapo.</i>

04:34.765 --> 04:36.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:36.767 --> 04:38.935
<i>Using his reputation
for brute violence,</i>

04:39.020 --> 04:43.023
<i>plus $2.5 million
worth of bribes,</i>

04:43.107 --> 04:45.200
<i>he soon makes the prison
a comfortable base</i>

04:45.359 --> 04:47.861
<i>from which to run his empire.</i>

04:47.954 --> 04:51.623
- The life that Chapo Guzmán
lived inside Puente Grande

04:51.708 --> 04:55.285
was almost more luxurious
than the Italian gangsters

04:55.378 --> 04:57.454
who were locked up,
you know, in "Goodfellas."

04:57.538 --> 05:00.132
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

05:00.291 --> 05:03.969
<i>He had his pick of liquor,
lobster, women.</i>

05:04.053 --> 05:08.724
<i>He was allowed to have visits
not only from his main wife,</i>

05:08.883 --> 05:10.809
<i>but from his second wife.</i>

05:10.968 --> 05:13.979
<i>He also had a prison girlfriend.</i>

05:14.138 --> 05:18.308
<i>He had--he essentially had
free access to telephones.</i>

05:18.392 --> 05:23.563
And all of this was possible
because he had befriended

05:23.656 --> 05:28.568
<i>the deputy warden for security
of Puente Grande,</i>

05:28.652 --> 05:31.071
a guy named Dámaso López.

05:31.164 --> 05:33.999
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

05:34.158 --> 05:37.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:37.328 --> 05:40.663
<i>López, who,
in exchange for small gifts,</i>

05:40.757 --> 05:43.666
<i>like cash and a nice house,</i>

05:43.760 --> 05:45.761
essentially gave Chapo Guzmán

05:45.920 --> 05:48.254
<i>the run of Puente Grande.</i>

05:48.339 --> 05:49.765
<i>- At some point, he had paid off</i>

05:49.849 --> 05:53.018
almost every single official
in the prison.

05:53.102 --> 05:56.679
- Chapo was still able
to organize drug shipments,

05:56.773 --> 05:59.191
even though he was within
Puente Grande prison.

05:59.350 --> 06:01.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:01.602 --> 06:03.603
<i>- It's at this time
that El Chapo makes</i>

06:03.687 --> 06:07.524
<i>a brilliant innovation in
the drug-trafficking business.</i>

06:07.617 --> 06:09.776
- How do you get anything
across what is

06:09.860 --> 06:11.194
a heavily-patrolled border?

06:11.278 --> 06:14.781
<i>What if you could evade
detection by going below?</i>

06:14.865 --> 06:18.368
<i>What if you could construct
an easy pathway from Mexico</i>

06:18.452 --> 06:19.869
<i>into the United States,</i>

06:19.954 --> 06:22.214
<i>one that was air conditioned,
one that had lighting,</i>

06:22.373 --> 06:24.132
<i>one that had
an elaborate railcar system</i>

06:24.291 --> 06:26.051
<i>that could transport hundreds,</i>

06:26.210 --> 06:28.804
<i>thousands of kilograms--
Marijuana,</i>

06:28.963 --> 06:32.132
cocaine, heroin,
methamphetamine?

06:32.216 --> 06:34.309
Well, if you could
figure that out,

06:34.468 --> 06:35.977
you'd be a successful man.

06:36.137 --> 06:38.647
<i>A man who pioneers the use</i>

06:38.806 --> 06:40.723
<i>of tunnels to transport
narcotics</i>

06:40.808 --> 06:45.737
across the United States-Mexico
border is El Chapo.

06:45.896 --> 06:49.574
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:49.733 --> 06:55.414
<i>- He employed highly-skilled
architects and engineers</i>

06:55.498 --> 06:58.241
to design these tunnels for him.

06:58.334 --> 07:02.838
<i>He managed to maintain
an operation</i>

07:02.922 --> 07:04.581
<i>that was netting him</i>

07:04.674 --> 07:07.926
<i>in the neighborhood
of $20 million a month.</i>

07:08.085 --> 07:12.839
Guzmán's empire grew
almost more than it had

07:12.932 --> 07:15.175
<i>before he was incarcerated.</i>

07:15.268 --> 07:18.261
<i>- El Chapo's business savvy
and the intense loyalty</i>

07:18.345 --> 07:20.430
<i>he instills in his underlings</i>

07:20.514 --> 07:25.026
<i>keeps the Sinaloa Cartel
running from behind bars.</i>

07:25.186 --> 07:28.113
<i>But all that is about to change.</i>

07:28.197 --> 07:30.190
- In the mid to late '90s,

07:30.274 --> 07:32.775
Mexico is not extraditing
Mexican nationals

07:32.860 --> 07:34.453
<i>to the United States.</i>

07:34.612 --> 07:37.113
<i>But something changed
beginning in 2001.</i>

07:37.198 --> 07:40.450
<i>The Mexican Supreme Court
issued an opinion saying</i>

07:40.543 --> 07:43.119
<i>that it would
restart extraditions</i>

07:43.212 --> 07:45.538
<i>of Mexican nationals
to the United States.</i>

07:45.631 --> 07:47.132
<i>And Chapo was not having it.</i>

07:47.216 --> 07:49.375
<i>- Hanging around
in his plush prison hideout</i>

07:49.460 --> 07:51.377
<i>is no longer an option.</i>

07:51.462 --> 07:53.472
<i>El Chapo is a sitting duck</i>

07:53.631 --> 07:56.808
<i>if he can't get
out of here--fast.</i>

07:58.311 --> 08:01.721
<i>- Chapo learns that he has
been charged</i>

08:01.814 --> 08:04.065
with drug trafficking crimes
here in the United States,

08:04.225 --> 08:05.650
and he's worried.
He's concerned that

08:05.809 --> 08:07.903
if he gets extradited
in the United States,

08:07.987 --> 08:09.812
he's not gonna have
the same ability

08:09.897 --> 08:11.981
<i>to control his cartel,</i>

08:12.066 --> 08:14.817
<i>give out instructions,
coordinate drug shipments</i>

08:14.902 --> 08:16.319
<i>from inside
a U.S. prison cell.</i>

08:16.403 --> 08:19.748
<i>So he realizes
that he has to get out.</i>

08:19.907 --> 08:22.242
- El Chapo isn't just
the mastermind

08:22.326 --> 08:25.745
of an international drug cartel.

08:25.829 --> 08:27.672
He's also an escape artist.

08:27.831 --> 08:29.591
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:29.675 --> 08:32.418
He knows he needs
to be very careful

08:32.503 --> 08:35.013
who he confides in
about his plans.

08:35.172 --> 08:36.848
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:37.007 --> 08:39.601
<i>- What you see is,
within a matter of weeks,</i>

08:39.760 --> 08:41.853
<i>Chapo put together
his escape plan</i>

08:41.938 --> 08:43.596
from Puente Grande Prison.

08:43.689 --> 08:47.267
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

08:47.360 --> 08:51.112
<i>- He orchestrates a complex
series of getaway vehicles</i>

08:51.197 --> 08:54.366
<i>to be put in place
for his jail break.</i>

08:54.525 --> 08:56.117
<i>He threatens the lives of anyone</i>

08:56.277 --> 08:58.870
<i>who could reveal the plan.</i>

08:59.029 --> 09:03.124
<i>And of course,
he greases a lot of palms.</i>

09:03.284 --> 09:04.450
<i>- For this escape,</i>

09:04.544 --> 09:08.380
<i>he bribed a much
smaller group of officials,</i>

09:08.464 --> 09:10.957
<i>the idea being
the fewer people that know,</i>

09:11.041 --> 09:12.467
<i>the less trouble there will be.</i>

09:12.626 --> 09:14.386
<i>And so ultimately,</i>

09:14.545 --> 09:17.714
he bribed one of the workers,
a man named Chito.

09:17.798 --> 09:23.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:23.554 --> 09:26.306
<i>- It's Chito's job to take
this laundry cart</i>

09:26.390 --> 09:28.733
out of the prison in a van,
and take the laundry

09:28.818 --> 09:30.986
to be cleaned
to bring it back to the prison.

09:31.070 --> 09:36.074
<i>- El Chito, or the Quiet One,
is a perfect accomplice,</i>

09:36.233 --> 09:38.994
<i>since, in his lowly
janitorial position,</i>

09:39.078 --> 09:41.913
<i>he's off the radar
of the other guards.</i>

09:42.072 --> 09:44.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:44.333 --> 09:46.501
[gate squeaks]

09:46.660 --> 09:49.421
- The Quiet One opens
his cell door,

09:49.580 --> 09:52.257
<i>helps him into a cart
of dirty laundry,</i>

09:52.416 --> 09:55.677
<i>conceals him,
walks him out of the cell.</i>

09:55.836 --> 09:58.504
- Chapo knows exactly
how many gates

09:58.598 --> 10:00.932
<i>he has to get through
in order to be free.</i>

10:01.091 --> 10:04.510
Now, at some point,
Chito lets go of the cart

10:04.604 --> 10:07.022
<i>in order to ask one of
the guards to open the gate.</i>

10:07.181 --> 10:08.857
<i>The cart starts rolling back,</i>

10:09.016 --> 10:11.434
<i>and Chapo winds up
being terrified</i>

10:11.527 --> 10:13.519
that the cart
is gonna spill over,

10:13.613 --> 10:15.447
<i>he'll fall out on the floor,</i>

10:15.606 --> 10:17.023
<i>and he'll be sent
right back to prison.</i>

10:17.116 --> 10:19.284
<i>But the cart stays upright.</i>

10:19.443 --> 10:22.945
<i>Chito collects it,
walks out of the prison,</i>

10:23.030 --> 10:25.031
<i>into the parking lot,
opens the trunk</i>

10:25.115 --> 10:28.034
<i>of a Chevy Monte Carlo
that El Chapo hops into,</i>

10:28.118 --> 10:30.620
<i>and then the prison guard
drives him away.</i>

10:30.704 --> 10:32.372
<i>- He's got a head start,</i>

10:32.456 --> 10:33.790
<i>thanks to having
the local police</i>

10:33.874 --> 10:35.216
<i>in his pocket.</i>

10:35.301 --> 10:39.045
<i>But federal law enforcement
gets word of the escape,</i>

10:39.138 --> 10:41.306
<i>and the chase is on.</i>

10:41.390 --> 10:43.049
<i>He still has a long,
dangerous road</i>

10:43.133 --> 10:44.476
<i>ahead of him to safety.</i>

10:44.635 --> 10:47.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:47.137 --> 10:49.889
- He was met by yet another car,

10:49.973 --> 10:53.068
<i>an armored Volkswagen,
so it is said,</i>

10:53.227 --> 10:55.228
<i>from which he was driven
to a place</i>

10:55.312 --> 10:57.489
<i>where he was picked up
in a helicopter.</i>

10:57.648 --> 11:00.983
<i>The helicopter flew him
to yet another location,</i>

11:01.077 --> 11:03.236
<i>where Guzmán got into
a third car,</i>

11:03.329 --> 11:07.323
<i>and made a multi-hour drive
from that secret location</i>

11:07.408 --> 11:09.409
<i>to Mexico City.</i>

11:09.493 --> 11:11.252
<i>Arriving in Mexico City,</i>

11:11.337 --> 11:13.496
Guzmán is said to have looked up

11:13.580 --> 11:15.164
<i>from the back seat
of the vehicle</i>

11:15.249 --> 11:17.092
<i>and seen police squad cars</i>

11:17.176 --> 11:19.335
and motorcycles surrounding him.

11:19.420 --> 11:23.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:23.674 --> 11:27.268
<i>- In the complex web of local,
state, and federal police,</i>

11:27.428 --> 11:30.012
<i>El Chapo can never be 100% sure</i>

11:30.106 --> 11:33.191
<i>who's clean and who's dirty.</i>

11:33.275 --> 11:36.185
- He nervously asks his driver,
"What's going on?"

11:36.278 --> 11:38.771
<i>And he was reassured,
"Don't worry, amigo.</i>

11:38.856 --> 11:40.699
<i>Those are our police."</i>

11:40.858 --> 11:43.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:43.369 --> 11:47.372
<i>- He has his own corrupt
Mexico City police officers</i>

11:47.531 --> 11:51.042
<i>form, essentially,
a motorcade to prevent</i>

11:51.201 --> 11:53.628
any other law enforcement
from stopping Chapo,

11:53.713 --> 11:56.706
and Chapo winds up
going to the safe house

11:56.799 --> 11:59.125
and essentially
starting up again.

11:59.209 --> 12:01.219
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:01.378 --> 12:03.129
<i>- So the fact that
he was able to escape,</i>

12:03.213 --> 12:05.131
waltz out of
the maximum-security prison

12:05.224 --> 12:07.633
at Puente Grande in 2001

12:07.727 --> 12:09.385
<i>creates the legend of Chapo</i>

12:09.478 --> 12:11.563
<i>as the uncatchable,
the untouchable.</i>

12:11.722 --> 12:14.566
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:18.738 --> 12:21.647
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:21.732 --> 12:25.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:25.494 --> 12:27.403
- After his escape
from this cell

12:27.488 --> 12:29.164
at Puente Grande,

12:29.248 --> 12:31.416
El Chapo manages
to stay out of the grip

12:31.575 --> 12:35.411
of the Mexican government
for more than a decade.

12:35.496 --> 12:38.831
- Even though El Chapo
is living as a fugitive

12:38.916 --> 12:41.092
in the remote mountain hideouts

12:41.177 --> 12:44.253
<i>that he has carved out
of these valleys and peaks,</i>

12:44.338 --> 12:49.258
<i>he is able to really become
the narcotrafficker</i>

12:49.351 --> 12:51.436
that we think of him
being today.

12:53.096 --> 12:57.776
<i>In the few years after Guzmán
escaped from Puente Grande</i>

12:57.860 --> 13:02.280
<i>and reignited
his American cocaine</i>

13:02.439 --> 13:05.274
<i>and heroin distribution
organization,</i>

13:05.359 --> 13:09.445
he was able to get almost
a billion dollars of cocaine

13:09.530 --> 13:12.707
to Chicago alone.

13:12.792 --> 13:17.962
- His empire grows by him
doing what he's always done--

13:18.047 --> 13:20.799
<i>Trafficking
ton quantities of drugs</i>

13:20.883 --> 13:22.375
<i>all over the world.</i>

13:22.459 --> 13:24.469
<i>[gunshots]</i>

13:24.628 --> 13:26.462
- It was during this time
that he decided

13:26.547 --> 13:28.807
that the way to control Mexico,

13:28.891 --> 13:30.725
the way to control
drug trafficking,

13:30.884 --> 13:32.635
was to do it violently.

13:32.728 --> 13:34.554
<i>So he went out from Sinaloa,</i>

13:34.638 --> 13:36.564
<i>which is on
the western side of Mexico,</i>

13:36.649 --> 13:41.143
<i>and he sent his soldiers
to places like Ciudad Juarez,</i>

13:41.228 --> 13:43.062
<i>Nuevo Laredo, Nuevo Leon,</i>

13:43.146 --> 13:45.907
<i>and you began to see these
really bloody turf battles</i>

13:45.991 --> 13:48.401
<i>that hadn't existed
in Mexico prior.</i>

13:48.485 --> 13:51.487
<i>You'd see these almost
military-esque war zones</i>

13:51.572 --> 13:52.664
